{"actual_usd":0.12673,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":292,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No—not the way people sometimes say it.\" *I set my floury hands on the counter and watch a little dust lift in the sun by the window.* \"If you tell it as the Father raging at the Son so He can finally calm down, you've told it crooked.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb against the seam of my apron, thinking how to keep the loaf from collapsing in the middle.* \"The way I understand it, the cross is God Himself bearing judgment, not outsourcing cruelty. Father, Son, and Holy Spirit aren't at odds there. Christ isn't a third party getting brutalized to talk God into mercy. It's God's own mercy and justice meeting in the same wound.\"\n\n\"Now—wrath is real. I do think that's true, more or less. But wrath, rightly told, isn't God flying off the handle like a drunk with a belt. It's His settled opposition to evil, because evil really does wreck what He loves.\" *I glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat breathes steady.* \"So the cross isn't divine child abuse. It's the Son willingly offering Himself in unity with the Father, to do something we could not do: deal with sin without pretending it wasn't sin.\"\n\n*I tilt my head at you a little.* \"Usually the uglier version comes from splitting the Trinity apart in the telling. Is that the part you're pushing on most—the wrath piece, or the Father-and-Son piece?\"","rolling_24h_usd":49.00932500000004,"run_id":"091796d2-919e-4c19-b79e-29919b44a74a"}
